AGI - In the European locomotive, tomorrow's legislative elections will also be a challenge to women, with Alice Weidel, Sarah Wagenknecht and Heidi Reichinnek who will compete for the place at the Bundeskanzleramt along with the probable future Chancellor Friedirich Merz, the leading Olof Scholz and the liberal Christian Lindner. All three leaders are leading radical parties, which are extreme right or extreme left.
&nbsp;
The first - in terms of consensus, since the polls give its stable party in second place with more than 20% - is Alice Weidel, 46 years old, head of Alternative fur Deutschland, extreme right-wing political formation. Eurosceptic and ultra-liberal, Weidel studied economics and trade at the University of Bayreuth and worked as an analyst at Goldman Sachs, before moving to China and obtaining a doctorate at the University of Bayreuth on the Chinese social security system.
&nbsp;
After working for Allianz Global Investors, Weidel joined AfD since its founding - initially in the Baden-Wurttemberg section - and became a member of the party's national council in 2015. 2017 is the turning year. Weidel - during the national congress of the party - is nominated as a leading candidate for the 2017 Bundestag elections, in which he is elected and appointed as a group leader in parliament.
&nbsp;
AfD's undisputed leader, in June 2022, was chosen - along with Tino Chupralla - as spokesman and guides the party throughout the growth path until the second place, last September, in the elections in Thuringia and Saxony. At the top of his agenda is immigration: He promised that, if in power, within the first 100 days the German borders will be "sealed" and there will be "wide-scale repatriations". In foreign policy, Weidel does not hide sympathy for the Kremlin and has repeatedly accused Ukraine of being partly responsible for the invasion of 2022.
&nbsp;
From the economic point of view, the AfD wants to relaunch the German economy with a strong deregulation, tax cuts and low-cost energy, thanks to nuclear and Russian gas imports. Finally, the Weidel - although she is married to a woman, with whom she grows two children - complains the decline of traditional families, but also claims that the AfD represents "the only real protection for gays and lesbians in Germany" against the threat of Muslims.
&nbsp;
The second female leader who in the last year made a lot of talk about himself is Sarah Wagenkncecht, 55-year-old, Bsw's leader, who was founded a year ago after leaving the Linke. 'Simprove Face' of the left and endowed with a strong charism, combines demands such as the fight against social inequality with proposals closer to the right - like the limitation of immigration. This mix often leads to being called 'red-brown'.
&nbsp;
With the Weidel, he shares the consensus exploit obtained in the regional elections in Saxony, Thuringia and Brandenburg - where his party emerged as a third force with 11.8% respectively, 15.8% and 13.5% of the votes - but unlike the extreme right leader, according to the latest polls, his entry into the federal chamber is strongly at risk. The polls credit it by approximately 4.5% of the consents, 0.5% less than the landing threshold. The third and last female leader who will run tomorrow in the elections is Heidi Reichinnek, candidate of the Linke together with party president Jan van Aken. Born of the extreme left, the thirty-six-year-old - who from 2021 is a member of the Bundestag and in his left arm has tattooed the face of Rosa Luxemburg - in the last month has managed to double his consents in the polls, up to reach even 7.5% at the expense also and especially of the Wagenkncecht. Become viral on social media for criticizing Friedrich Merz, who had sought the votes of the extreme right for his immigration proposals, Reichinnek is the most followed German policy on TikTok, a platform on which he exposes his progressive vision focused on the fight against expensive rents and increased taxes for the richest.
&nbsp;
According to Klaus-Peter Schoppner, an expert German poll, the success of the Reichinnek and as a result of the Linke - unthinkable only until a month ago - is explained by his ability to attract, especially through a broad use of social media, the attention of the younger voters. On the growth of the party and its leader, there is then a purely reason for themes and programs, since - with the now conclaimed crisis of the SPD - it represents the only political force able to voice the instances of the 'common people', and at the same time to communicate the traditional messages of the left effectively and credible, first to the young generations. &nbsp;

