AGI - With a choreography that has now been tested and repeated every week, Hamas has released six other Israeli hostages, the last alive of those planned in the first phase of the agreement for the ceasefire in Gaza. In addition to the joy of family members, friends and activists, there is uncertainty for the other kidnapped prisoners still in the Strip, since the negotiations for the second stage have not yet been started and it is feared that the understanding may stop.
Hamas reiterated that he was ready to free them all together, at once, in exchange for the permanent cessation of fighting and the complete withdrawal of troops from Gaza. Two conditions that the extreme right to the government with Benjamin Netanyahu does not seem willing to accept, risking the survival of the same executive.
Israeli president Isaac Herzog expressed joy for the liberation of the six hostages and urged the conclusion of the agreement, calling it "a human, moral and Jewish act". On the same line the opposition leader Yair Lapid, for which &nbsp; "the government must choose life instead of pain and proceed towards the second stage of the exchange agreement".
At the same time, the Arab countries of the Gulf together with Egypt and Jordan work on a plan for Gaza alternative to that proposed by American President Donald Trump, which provides for the forced displacement of Palestinians. After yesterday's informal summit in Riyadh, the meeting of the Arab League in Cairo was scheduled for March 4.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The first two hostages to be delivered to the Red Cross were&nbsp;Tal Shoham and Avera Mengistu, the first kidnapped on October 7 while he was at the home of the Sisters in the Kibbutz Be'eri and the second, with mental problems, voluntarily entered more than ten ago in the Strip and taken prisoner.
The ceremony took place in Rafah, where a stage was set up and the two men were shown to the crowd, among slogans and armed militiamen in mass who presided over the place, before being transferred to the hands of officials of the Icrc who signed their 'sign'.
Eliya Cohen, Omer Shem Tov and Omer Wenkert,&nbsp; dressed in a military 'divisa', were released to Nuseirat. Same choreography, with a crowd waiting around the stage and ironic phrases addressed to Netanyahu and his promises to release them "only thanks to military pressure". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The last was &nbsp;Hisham al-Sayed, which Hamas delivered to the Red Cross in Gaza, without the humiliating procedure imposed on others, as a sign of respect for his Bedouin family and the Arab-Israeli living in the Jewish State. Faced with mental problems, the 37-year-old had voluntarily entered the Strip in 2015. His last life test was released in June 2022 with a video showing him sick in a hospital bed &nbsp; with an oxygen mask and an IV. &nbsp;
In exchange for the six hostages, Israel has agreed to the dismissal of &nbsp;602 Palestinian prisoners, including &nbsp;60 who are serving long sentences, 50 Ergastolani, 47 who were released as part of the exchange in 2011 for Glad Shalit and over 100 who will be immediately. &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
Also this week Israel responded to Hamas' liberation ceremonies-shows of hostages by imposing on Palestinian prisoners to release a T-shirt with writing, "I will chase my enemies and reach them, and I will not return until they are destroyed", along with a bracelet with the written "the eternal people does not forget, I will chase my enemies and reach them". &nbsp; &nbsp; Last week, inmates had been forced to wear T-shirts before scarceness: "We won't forget, we won't forgive." T-shirts burned in favor of room immediately after arrival in Gaza.
&nbsp;

